ics of the Hilbert Transformer -- t4.5 Receiving an SSB Signal -- t4.6 Weaver’s SSB Transmitter -- t5 FM Radio -- t5.1 Why FM? -- t5.2 Instantaneous Frequency -- t5.3 FM Sidebands -- t5.4 The FM Receiver -- t5.5 Bilotti’s Phase Quadrature Detector -- t6 American AM Broadcast Radio: A Historical Postscript -- tA Final Author’s Note to the Reader -- tAppendix—Maxwell’s Theory, the Poynting Vector, and a Simple Radio Transmitting Antenna -- tSolutions, Partial Answers, and More Hints to Most of the End-of- Chapter Challenge Problems -- tAcknowledgments -- tIllustration Credits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow a modern radio works, told through mathematics, history, and selected puzzlesThe modern radio is a wonder, and behind that magic is mathematics. In The Mathematical Radio, Paul Nahin explains how radios work, deploying mathematics and historical discussion, accompanied by a steady stream of intriguing puzzles for math buffs to ponder. Beginning with oscillators and circuits, then moving on to AM, FM, and single-sideband radio, Nahin focuses on the elegant mathematics underlying radio technology rather than the engineering. He explores and explains more than a century of key developments, placing them in historical and technological context.Nahin, a prolific author of books on math for the general reader, describes in fascinating detail the mathematical underpinnings of a technology we use daily. He explains and solves, for example, Maxwell’s equations for the electromagnetic field. Readers need only a familarity with advanced high school–level math to follow Nahin’s mathematical discussions. Writing with the nonengineer in mind, Nahin examines topics including impulses in time and frequency, spectrum shifting at the transmitter, the superheterodyne, the physics of single-sideband radio, and FM sidebands. Chapters end with “challenge problems” and an appendix offers solutions, partial answers, and hints. Readers will come away with a new appreciation for the beauty of even the most useful mathematics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aRadio circuitsxMathematical models. 0aRadioxTransmitters and transmissionxMathematics. 7aTechnology & Engineering / Radio.2bisacsh  aAM/FM radio theory.  aG. H. Hardy.  aPaul J. Nahin.  aThe Mathematical Radio: Inside the Magic of AM, FM, Single-Sideband, and Wifi.  aapplied mathematics.  abroadcast radio history.  acircuits.  aelectronic inventions.  ahistory important technology.  ahistory of knowledge.  ahistory of mathematics.  ahow does radio work.  amath behind radio.  amath.  amathematical underpinnings.  amathematics.  aoscillators.  apivotal technology.  aprinceton university press.  aradio engineering.  aradio.  asingleband.  awifi.1 aSimoson, Andrew J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimoson, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074975540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691235325?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691235325423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691235325/original  a978-3-11-074975-5  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles